> If ever a curry can be described as soothing, it's the korma. Ground almonds help make the sauce even more velvety and honey adds a touch of sweetness. Yes, there's a bit of spice but nothing to be afraid of!

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1} into half moons. Peel and grate the @ginger{} and @garlic cloves{3} (or use a garlic press). Chop the @British chicken breasts{3} into 2cm pieces. Trim the tops off the @green beans{1} and chop them into three pieces. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(stalks and all).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the chicken and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and some @black pepper{some}. Cook until the chicken is browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes} (do this in batches if your pan is small). Add the onion and cook until softened, ~{5%minutes}. Add the ginger, @korma spice mix{1} and the garlic. Stir together and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

While the chicken is cooking, pour the @water{600%ml} for the rice into a large #saucepan{} on high heat. Add half the @chicken stock pot{1} and stir to dissolve. Add the @star anise{1}. Bring to the boil then add the @basmati rice{300%g}. Cook for ~{10%minutes}. Remove the pan from the heat and leave to rest with the lid on for ~{10%minutes}. The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Pour the @water{600%ml} for the curry into the pan with the chicken, along with the remaining stock pot, @ground almonds{40%g}, @raisins{40%g}, @honey{1%tbsp} and @double cream{150%ml}. Stir together and bring to the boil. Reduce the heat to medium-low and simmer gently for ~{10%minutes}. Add the green beans and cook until they are done and the curry has thickened, another ~{5-7%minutes}.

Stir in the @baby spinach{1} and cook until wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Then stir through half the parsley.

Remove the star anise from the rice and fluff it up with a #fork{}. Serve in bowls with a generous spoonful of curry on top, sprinkled with the remaining parsley. Enjoy!